Exercise 16 - Let $(X,M,\mu)$ be a measure space. A set $E\subset X$ is called locally measurable if $E\cap A\in M$ for all $A\in M$ such that $\mu(A) < \infty$. Let $	ilde{M}$ be the collection of all locally measurable sets. Clearly, $M\subset 	ilde{M}$, if $M = 	ilde{M}$, then $\mu$ is saturated. a.) If $\mu$ is $\sigma$-finite, then $\mu$ is saturated. Proof - Suppose $\mu$ is $\sigma$-finite. Let $A\in	ilde{M}$, and let $X =  igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_j$ where $E_j\in M$ and $\mu(E_j) < \infty$ for all $j$. We know $M\subset 	ilde{M}$ what we want to show is that $	ilde{M}\subset M$. We can write $$A = A\cap X = A\cap \left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_jight) =  igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_j\cap A$$ Since $\mu(E_j)<\infty$ we have $E_j\cap A\in M$ for all $j$. Therefore, $	ilde{M}\subset M$, thus $\mu$ is saturated. b.) $	ilde{M}$ is $\sigma$-algebra. Proof - i.) $\emptyset\in M\subset 	ilde{M}$, so $\emptyset\in 	ilde{M}$. ii.) Let $B\in 	ilde{M}$. Take any $E\in M$ such that $\mu(E) < \infty$. Then $$E\setminus B = E\cap B^c = E\cap (E\cap B)^c$$ since $E\in M$ and $(E\cap B)\in M$ then $(E\cap (E\cap B)^c\in M$. Thus we have $B^c\in 	ilde{M}$. iii.) Let $\{B_j\}_{1}^{\infty}\in 	ilde{M}$. Take any $E\in M$ with $\mu(E)< \infty$. Then, $$\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}B_jight)\cap E =  igcup_{1}^{\infty}(B_j\cap E)\in M$$  so, by definition of $	ilde{M}$, $ igcup_{1}^{\infty}B_j\in 	ilde{M}$. Therefore $	ilde{M}$ us a $\sigma$-algebra. c.) Define $	ilde{\mu}$ on $	ilde{M}$ by $	ilde{\mu}(E) = \mu(E)$ if $E\in M$ and $	ilde{\mu}(E) = \infty$ otherwise. Then $	ilde{\mu}$ is a saturated measure on $	ilde{M}$, called the saturation of $\mu$. Step 1: Show that $	ilde{\mu}$ is a measure on $	ilde{M}$. Proof - i.) $	ilde{\mu}(\emptyset) = \mu(\emptyset) = 0$. ii.) Let $\{E_j\}_{1}^{\infty}\in 	ilde{M}$ that is pairwise disjoint. Let $$E =  igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_j$$ If $E \in M$ then  egin{align*} 	ilde{\mu}(E) = 	ilde{\mu}\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_jight) &= \mu\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_jight)\ &= \sum_{1}^{\infty}\mu(E_j)\ &= \sum_{1}^{\infty}	ilde{\mu}(E_j) \end{align*} If $E
otin M$ then $	ilde{\mu}(E) = \infty$... not sure where to go from here. Step 2 - $	ilde{\mu}$ is saturated. Proof - Let $E\subset X$ such that $E\cap A\in 	ilde{M}$ when $	ilde{\mu}(A) < \infty$. Choose a $B\in M$ such that $\mu(B)<\infty$. Then, clearly $	ilde{\mu}(B)<\infty$ and $E\cap B\in 	ilde{M}$. So, $E\cap B = (E\cap B)\cap B\in M$ so $E\in 	ilde{M}$ it thus follows that $	ilde{\mu}$ is saturated. d.) If $\mu$ is complete, so is $	ilde{\mu}$. Proof - Suppose $\mu$ is complete. Let $A\subset X$ and suppose there is a $B\in 	ilde{M}$ such that $A\subset B$ and $\mu(B) = 0$. Since $B\in	ilde{M}$ and $\mu(B) = 0$ then $	ilde{\mu}(B) < \infty$ and hence $B\in M$. This, since $A\subset B$ we have $A\in M$ by completeness of $\mu$. Therefore, $A\in 	ilde{M}$ and $	ilde{\mu}$ is complete. e.) Suppose that $\mu$ is semifinite. For $E\in	ilde{M}$, define $\underline{\mu}(E) = \sup\{\mu(A):A\in M, A\subset E\}$. Then $\underline{\mu}$ is a saturated measure on $	ilde{M}$ that extends $\mu$. Step 1 - $\underline{\mu}$ is a measure. Proof - i.) $\overline{\mu}(\emptyset) = \mu(\emptyset) = 0$ ii.) Let $\{E_j\}_{1}^{\infty}$ be a sequence of disjoint sets in $	ilde{M}$. Set, $$E =  igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_j$$ then by definition of $	ilde{M}$ there is an $A\in M$ and $A\subset E$. Case 1 - $\mu(A) < \infty$. Then $$\mu(A) = \mu\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_j\cap Aight) = \sum_{1}^{\infty}\mu(E_j\cap A)\leq \sum_{1}^{\infty}\underline{\mu}(E_j)$$ Case 2 - $\mu(A) = \infty$. By semifiniteness, for all $C>0$ there exists a $F\subset A$ such that $F\in M$ and $\mu(F) = C$. Then by case 1, $\leq \sum_{1}^{\infty}\underline{\mu}(E_j) = \infty$. Therefore, $\mu(A) \leq \sum_{1}^{\infty}\underline{\mu}(E_j)$. Taking the supremum over all $A$ we have $$\underline{\mu}\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_jight)\leq \sum_{1}^{\infty}\underline{\mu}(E_j)$$ Now we need to show the reverse inequality. By the definition of supremum there exists a sequence $\{B_i\}_{1}^{\infty}\in M$ and $B_i\subset E_i$ for all $i$. Thus, $\underline{\mu}(E_i)\leq \mu(B_i) + \epsilon 2^{-i}$. Therefore,   egin{align*} \sum_{1}^{\infty}\underline{\mu}(E_i) &\leq \sum_{1}^{\infty}\mu(B_i) + \epsilon\ &= \mu\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}B_iight) + \epsilon \ \ 	ext{is this true because of case 1?}\ &\leq \underline{\mu}\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_iight) + \epsilon \end{align*} Since this holds for all $\epsilon > 0$, we have $$\sum_{1}^{\infty}\underline{\mu}(E_j)\leq \underline{\mu}\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_jight)$$ Therefore, $$\underline{\mu}\left( igcup_{1}^{\infty}E_jight) = \sum_{1}^{\infty}\underline{\mu}(E_j)$$ and hence $\underline{\mu}$ is a measure. Step 2 - $\underline{\mu}$ is saturated. Proof - Let $E\subset X$ be such that $E\cap A\in 	ilde{M}$ when $\underline{\mu}(A)< \infty$. Take any $B\in M$ such that $\mu(B) < \infty$. Then $\underline{\mu}(B) < \infty$ so $E\cap B\in 	ilde{M}$. Thus, $E\cap B = (E\cap B)\cap B\in M$ and $E\in	ilde{M}$, hence, $\underline{\mu}$ is saturated. Step 3 - $\underline{\mu}$ is an extention of $\mu$. Proof - Let $E\in M$. For any $A\in M$ such that $A\subset E$, we have by monotonicity that $\mu(A)\leq \mu(E)$. Since $\underline{\mu}(E)$ is the supremum over all such $A$, we must have that $\underline{\mu}(E)\leq \mu(E)$. OTOH.... not sure how to show the reverse inequality. f.) Let $X_1$ and $X_2$ be disjoint uncountable sets, $X = X_1\cup X_2$, and $M$ the $\sigma$-alegbra of countable or co-countable sets in $X$. Let $\mu_0$ be counting measure on $\mathcal{P}(X_1)$ and define $\mu$ on $M$ by $\mu(E) = \mu_0(E\cap X_1)$. Then $\mu$ is a measure on $M$, $	ilde{M} = \mathcal{P}(X)$, and in the notation of parts (c) and (e), $	ilde{\mu}
